INSERT INTO `quiz` VALUES (1,3,'Types of Functions','What type of function is represented here?','','Absolute-Value-Functions-2.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','Quadratic','Linear','Absolute\\ Value','Square','','Absolute\\ Value',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Absolute-Value-Functions-2.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p>Remember the major type of function in Algebra 1 that you see as a \"V\" are ABSOLUTE VALUE FUNCTIONS. These functions always have the same y-values for the positive and negative version of each x-coordinate.</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:52:25'),(2,3,'Transformation of Functions','Is this transformation a vertical or horizontal reflection?','y = x^2\\ becomes\\ y = -x^2 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','Horizontal\\ Reflection','Vertical\\ Reflection',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Horizontal\\ Reflection',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> y\\ =\\ x^2\\ \\ becomes\\ y\\ =\\ -x^2 </tex></p> <p>This transformation is a HORIZONTAL reflection because the negative sign is OUTSIDE the function.</p> <p> If this was a VERTICAL reflection, the negative sign would be INSIDE the function: <tex> (-x)^2</tex>.</p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 14:56:23'),(3,3,'Transformation of Functions','What transformation is displayed in this function?','y=5x\\ becomes\\ y=5\\ \\left(x+2\\right)',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','Moving\\ 2\\ to\\ left','Moving \\ 2\\ to \\ right','Moving \\ up \\ 2','Moving \\ down \\ 2',NULL,'Moving\\ 2\\ to\\ left',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>y\\ =\\ 5x\\ becomes\\ y\\ =\\ 5\\left(x+2\\right)</tex></p> <p>The transformation for this problem is going to be a HORIZONTAL translation because it is inside of PARENTHESES. </p><p>Since + inside the parentheses corresponds to a translation to the left, the function <tex> y = 5^x </tex>is translated 2 units to the LEFT.</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:52:25'),(4,3,'Evaluating Functions','What is the output of this function when the input  is 11?','y=8x + 3',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','814','91','1','85',NULL,'91',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>y\\ =\\ 8x\\ +\\ 3</tex></p><p> Since 11 is the input to this function, plug in 11 where you see x in this function. Then, solve it to find y, the output.</p><p><tex>y\\ =\\ 8\\left(11\\right)\\ +\\ 3</tex></p><p><tex>y\\ =\\ 88\\ +\\ 3</p><p><tex>y\\ =\\ 91</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:02:52'),(5,3,'Composition of Functions','What is (f · g) (5)? Only type in the number.','f\\left(x\\right)\\ =\\ x^2 \\\\ g\\left(x\\right)\\ =\\ x\\ +\\ 2\\ \\ ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'(f ·  g) (5)=',NULL,NULL,'49',NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> f\\left(x\\right)\\ =\\ x^2\\ and\\ g\\left(x\\right)\\ =\\ x\\ +2 </tex></p> <p> To find (f · g) (5), you need to plug in 5 for x in g(x) before plugging in the output from g(5) into f(x) to get the final answer.</p> <p><tex> g\\left(5\\right)\\ =\\ 5\\ +\\ 2 </tex></p> <p><tex> g\\left(5\\right)\\ \\ =\\ 7 </tex></p> <p><tex> (f\\ · \\ g)\\ (5)\\ =\\ 7^2 </tex></p> <p><tex> (f\\ · \\ g)\\ (5)\\ =\\ 49 </tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 14:33:53'),(6,3,'Evaluating Functions','What is the positive input to this function when the output is 12?','y\\ =\\ 2x^2\\ +\\ 4',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','2','292','4','52',NULL,'2',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> y\\ =\\ 2x^2\\ +\\ 4 </tex></p> <p> Since 12 is the output to this function, plug in 12 where you see y in this function. Then, solve for x, the input to this function.</p> <p><tex> 12\\ =\\ 2x^2\\ +\\ 4 </tex></p> <p><tex> 8\\ =\\ 2x^2 </tex></p> <p><tex> 4\\ =\\ x^2 </tex></p> <p><tex> \\sqrt{4}\\ =\\ \\sqrt{x^2} </tex></p> <p><tex> x\\ =\\ 2 </tex></p> <p> Remember you only want the positive solution, so x = -2 is NOT correct here. </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:55:46'),(7,3,'Writing Functions','Write the function that is represented in this table.','','Writing-Functions-Table.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y\\ =\\ 4x\\ +\\ 2','y\\ =\\ 4x\\ +\\ 4 ','y\\ =\\ 2x\\ +\\ 2','y\\ =\\ 4x ',NULL,'y\\ =\\ 4x ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Writing-Functions-Table.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p>The function we are trying to write here is linear because the change in y for the change in x is the same. Find the slope first. We can use (1, 4) and (2, 8) to calculate the slope.</p> <p><tex> Slope\\ =\\ \\frac{8\\ -\\ 4}{2\\ -\\ 4}\\ =\\ 4 </tex></p> <p> Plug in the slope to y = mx + b and find b.</p> <p><tex> y = 4x + b </tex></p> <p><tex> 4= 4\\left(1\\right) + b \\rightarrow 4 = 4 + b \\rightarrow b = 0 </tex></p> <p><tex> y = 4x </tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:04:17'),(8,3,'Introduction to Functions ','What is the domain of this function?  ','','Function-as-a-Table.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','D\\ :\\ \\left\\{10,20,30,40\\right\\} ',' D\\ :\\ \\left\\{15,45,25,35\\right\\} ','D\\ :\\ \\left\\{10,20,25,35\\right\\} ','D\\ :\\ \\left\\{10,15,20,25\\right\\} ',NULL,'D\\ :\\ \\left\\{10,20,30,40\\right\\} ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Function-as-a-Table.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> The domain of a function refers to all of its X-VALUES or INPUTS. For this table, they are 10, 20, 30 and 40. </p> <p> Make sure to put this in set notation as {10, 20, 30, 40}. </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 14:36:08'),(9,3,'Introduction to  Functions','Is this graph a function based on the vertical line test? Type either yes or no.','','Function-VLT.png',NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'no',NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Function-VLT.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> This graph is NOT a function because if you draw a vertical line at any x-coordinate that is greater than 0, the line would cross the graph 2 times. </p> <p> Remember for the vertical line test, a vertical line drawn at any x-coordinate for a graph can only pass through it ONCE. </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(10,3,'Types of Functions ','What type of function is represented here? ','','Quadratic-Functions-2.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','Exponential','Linear','Cube','Quadratic',NULL,'Quadratic',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Quadratic-Functions-2.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> Remember the U-SHAPED functions that you learn in Algebra 1 are QUADRATIC FUNCTIONS. These functions always have the same y-values for the positive and negative version of each x-coordinate. </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(11,6,'Adding and Subtracting Radicals','What is the result when these 2 radicals are added together?','√50 + √32',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','45√2','41√2','9√2','√82',NULL,'9√2',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\">&radic;50 + &radic;32</p> <p>Before we add these radicals, we need to first find the highest perfect square factor from both radicals that we can pull out so that the number inside the radical is the same for both and we can add them together.</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 50: 1 and 50, 2 and 25, 5 and 10</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 32: 1 and 32, 2 and 16, 4 and 8</p> <p>Since the highest perfect square factor of 50 is 25 and the highest for 32 is 16, pull out the SQUARE ROOTS of these numbers (5 and 4, respectively), leaving 2 inside the radical for both. Then, add the numbers on the outside of each radical together.</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\">5&radic;2 + 4&radic;2 = 9&radic;2</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:47:21'),(12,6,'Converting between Rational Exponents and Radicals','Convert this rational exponent to a radical.','x^{\\frac{2}{3}}',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\sqrt[3]{x^{2}}','\\sqrt[3]{x^{6}}','\\sqrt{x^{3}}','\\sqrt[3]{x}',NULL,'\\sqrt[3]{x^{2}}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>x^{\\frac{2}{3}}</tex></p> <p>To convert rational exponents to radicals, remember that the DENOMINATOR of the exponent becomes the INDEX (number on the radical) and the NUMERATOR of the exponent is what x is raised to INSIDE of the radical.</p> <p>So, the conversion here would give us:</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\sqrt[3]{x^{2}}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:34:59'),(13,6,'Laws of Exponents','What is the result when these 2 terms are multiplied together?','x^{3}\\cdot x^{4}',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','7x^{7}','x^{7}','x^{12}','7x^{12}',NULL,'x^{7}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>x^{3}\\cdot x^{4}</tex></p> <p>Using the laws of exponents, when we multiply these 2 terms, we are simply ADDING the 2 exponents while keeping the same base.</p> <p>So, the answer here would be:</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>x^{7}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(14,6,'Multiplying and Dividing Radicals','What is the result when these 2 radicals are multiplied together?','\\sqrt{18}\\cdot \\sqrt{5}',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','9\\sqrt{10}','3\\sqrt{10}','\\sqrt{23}','6\\sqrt{5}',NULL,'3\\sqrt{10}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\sqrt{18}\\cdot \\sqrt{5}</tex></p> <p>When multiplying radicals, first multiply the numbers INSIDE the radicals first.</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\sqrt{18}\\cdot \\sqrt{5}=\\sqrt{90}</tex></p> <p>Then, we can go ahead and simplify the resulting radical. Pull out the square root of the highest perfect square factor of 90 and keep the other number in its factor pair INSIDE the radical.</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 90: 1 and 90, 2 and 45, 3 and 30, 5 and 18, 6 and 15, 9 and 10</p><p style=\"text-align: center;\">&radic;9 &middot; &radic;10</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>3\\sqrt{10}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:48:25'),(15,6,'Converting between Rational Exponents and Radicals','Convert this radical into a rational exponent.','\\sqrt[4]{x^{5}}',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','x^{\\frac{5}{4}}','x^{\\frac{4}{5}}','x^{\\frac{1}{5}}','x^{\\frac{1}{4}}',NULL,'x^{\\frac{4}{5}}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\sqrt[4]{x^{5}}</tex></p> <p>To convert this radical to a rational exponent, remember that the INDEX of the radical (the number attached to the radical) is the DENOMINATOR of the rational exponent and the number x is raised to is the NUMERATOR of the rational exponent.</p> <p>So, the conversion here would be:</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>x^{\\frac{4}{5}}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(16,6,'Laws of Exponents','What is the result after simplifying this expression?','\\frac{1}{x^{-2}}',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','-x^{2}','x^{2}','x^{-2}','-x^{-2}',NULL,'x^{2}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\frac{1}{x^{-2}}</tex></p> <p>Remember for negative exponents, if they are in the denominator, they need to come up to the NUMERATOR so the exponent can be positive.</p> <p>So, the answer here would be:</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>x^{2}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:34:59'),(17,6,'Adding and Subtracting Radicals','What is the result when these 2 radicals are subtracted from each other?','\\sqrt{75}-\\sqrt{12}',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','19\\sqrt{3}','\\sqrt{63}','21\\sqrt{3}','3\\sqrt{3}',NULL,'3\\sqrt{3}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\sqrt{75}-\\sqrt{12}</tex></p> <p>Before we subtract these radicals, we need to first find the highest perfect square factor from both radicals that we can pull out so that the number inside the radical is the same for both and we can subtract them together.</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 75: 1 and 75, 3 and 25, 5 and 15</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 12: 1 and 12, 2 and 6, 3 and 4</p> <p>Since the highest perfect square factor of 75 is 25 and the highest for 12 is 4, pull out the SQUARE ROOTS of these numbers (5 and 2, respectively), leaving 3&nbsp;inside the radical for both. Then, subtract the numbers on the outside of each radical together.</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>5\\sqrt{3}-2\\sqrt{3}=3\\sqrt{3}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(18,6,'Multiplying and Dividing Radicals','What is the result when these 2 radicals are divided by each other?','\\frac{\\sqrt{128}}{\\sqrt{32}}',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','2','\\sqrt{96}','48\\sqrt{2}','4',NULL,'2',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\frac{\\sqrt{128}}{\\sqrt{32}}</tex></p> <p>First, simplify each radical by pulling out the square root of the highest perfect square factor before we divide.</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 128: 1 and 128, 2 and 64, 4 and 32, 8 and 16</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 32: 1 and 32, 2 and 16, 4 and 8</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\sqrt{128}\\rightarrow 8\\sqrt{2}\\ and\\ \\sqrt{32}\\rightarrow 4\\sqrt{2}</tex></p> <p>Now divide the radicals, making sure to only divide numbers by numbers and radicals by radicals.</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\frac{8\\sqrt{2}}{4\\sqrt{2}}=2</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(19,6,'Laws of Exponents','What is the result when these 2 terms are divided by each other?','\\frac{x^{8}}{x^{2}} ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','6x^{6}','6x^{4}','x^{4}','x^{6}',NULL,'x^{6}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\frac{x^{8}}{x^{2}}</tex></p> <p>Using the laws of exponents, we can SUBTRACT the exponents in this problem while keeping the bases the same.</p> <p>So, the answer here would be:</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>x^{6}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(20,6,'Multiplying and Dividing Radicals','What is the result when these 2 radicals are divided by each other?','\\frac{\\sqrt{90}}{\\sqrt{6}}',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\sqrt{84}','3\\sqrt{5}','\\sqrt{15}','3\\sqrt{15}',NULL,'\\sqrt{15}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\frac{\\sqrt{90}}{\\sqrt{6}}</tex></p> <p>First, simplify each radical by pulling out the square root of the highest perfect square factor before we divide.</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 90: 1 and 90, 2 and 45, 3 and 30, 6 and 15, 9 and 10</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 6: 1 and 6, 2 and 3</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\sqrt{90}\\rightarrow 3\\sqrt{10}\\ and\\ \\sqrt{6}\\rightarrow \\sqrt{6}</tex></p> <p>Since the numbers inside the radicals are not the same, it would be better to just divide the numbers inside the radicals to get the answer (You can do this if the radicals don\'t cancel!)</p> <p style=\"text-align: center;\"><tex>\\frac{\\sqrt{90}}{\\sqrt{6}}= \\sqrt{15}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(21,2,'Basics of Polynomial','Order this polynomial correctly from highest to lowest degree. Watch your signs!','15x^3-35x^4+26x+5-88x^2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','-88x^2-35x^4+26x+15x^3+5','-35x^4+15x^3-88x^2+26x+5','35x^4+15x^3+88x^2+26x+5 ','15x^3-35x^4-88x^2+26x+5',NULL,'-35x^4+15x^3-88x^2+26x+5',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p> <tex> 15x^3\\ -\\ 35x^4\\ +\\ 26x\\ +\\ 5\\ -\\ 88x^2 </tex> </p> <p> To order a polynomial correctly, we need to separate the terms based on their exponents so we can order it from highest to lowest. </p> <p> When we do that, the terms in order from highest to lowest exponent would be: </p> <p><tex> -35x^4\\ +\\ 15x^3\\ -\\ 88x^2\\ +\\ 26x\\ +5 </tex> </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-17 13:06:29'),(22,2,'Adding and Subtracting Polynomials','What polynomial is the result of adding these two polynomials?','8x^2+12x+5\\ +\\  4x^2-8x+2 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','12x^4\\ +\\ 4x^2\\ +\\ 7','12x^2\\ +\\ 20x\\ +\\ 7','12x^2\\ +\\ 4x\\ +\\ 3','12x^2\\ - \\ 4x\\ +\\ 7',NULL,'12x^2\\ - \\ 4x\\ +\\ 7',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p> <tex> 8x^2+12x+5\\ +\\ 4x^2-8x+2 </tex> </p> <p> To add these polynomials, line them up where the<tex> x^2 </tex> terms for both polynomials are in the first column, the x terms for both polynomials are in the second column and the constants for both polynomials are in the last column. Then, add coefficients/constants to get the answer. </p> <p> <tex> 8x^2\\ +\\ 4x\\ +\\ 5 </tex></p> <p><tex> +\\ 4x^2\\ -\\ 8x\\ +\\ 2 </tex> </p> <p><tex> \\frac{ }{12x^2\\ -\\ 4x\\ +\\ 7} </tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:35:20'),(23,2,'Multiplying Polynomials using FOIL','What trinomial results from the multiplication of these 2 binomials?','\\left(x\\ +\\ 4\\right)\\ \\left(x-6\\right) ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','x^2\\ -\\ 2x\\ -\\ 24','x^2\\ +\\ 2x\\ -\\ 24','x^2\\ -\\ 2x\\ +\\ 24','x^2\\ +10x\\ -\\ 24',NULL,'x^2\\ -\\ 2x\\ -\\ 24',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p> <tex> \\left(x\\ +\\ 4\\right)\\ \\left(x-6\\right) </tex> </p> <p> To multiply these binomials, use FOIL! FOIL stands for First Outer Inner Last. Do these steps to find the trinomial that results from multiplying these binomials. </p> <p><tex> First (F) -\\ x\\ \\cdot \\ x\\ =\\ x^2 </tex></p> <p><tex> Outer (O) -\\ x\\ \\cdot \\ \\left(-6\\right)\\ =\\ -6x </tex></p> <p><tex> Inner (I) -\\ x\\ \\cdot \\ 4\\ =\\ 4x </tex></p>  <p><tex> Last (L) -4\\ \\cdot \\ \\left(-6\\right)\\ =\\ -24 </tex></p> <p> Put the terms together with their respective signs and combine like terms to get the final trinomial. </p> <p><tex> x^2\\ -\\ 6x\\ +\\ 4x\\ -\\ 24 </tex></p> <p><tex> x^2\\ -\\ 2x\\ -\\ 24 </tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(24,2,'Multiplying Polynomials using the Distributive Property','What is the result after using the distributive property?','4xy\\left(8x^2y\\ +\\ 12xy\\ \\ +\\ 25\\right) ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','32x^3y^2\\ +\\ 48x^2y^2\\ +\\ 100 ','12x^2y^2\\ +\\ 16xy^2\\ +\\ 100xy ','32x^3y^2\\ +\\ 48x^2y^2\\ +\\ 100xy ','32x^3y^2\\ +\\ 48x^2y^2\\ +\\ 29xy ',NULL,'32x^3y^2\\ +\\ 48x^2y^2\\ +\\ 100xy ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p> To solve this using the distributive property, we need to multiply 4xy to EACH term inside the parentheses. </p> <p> <tex> 4xy\\ \\cdot \\ 8x^2y\\ =\\ 32x^3y^2 </tex> </p> <p> <tex>4xy\\ \\cdot \\ 12xy\\ =\\ 48x^2y^2 </tex> </p> <p><tex> 4xy\\ \\cdot \\ 25\\ =\\ 100xy</tex> </p> <p> Now put addition signs between these terms to get the answer. </p> <p><tex> 32x^3y^2\\ +\\ 48x^2y^2\\ +\\ 100xy</tex> </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:37:16'),(25,2,'Basics of Polynomials','What is the degree of the following polynomial?','7x^3\\ +\\ 10\\ -\\ 45x\\ +\\ 15x^2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','3','7','-45','2',NULL,'3',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> 7x^3\\ +\\ 10\\ -\\ 45x\\ +\\ 15x^2 </tex></p> <p> To find the degree of the polynomial, we need to find the term with the highest exponent in this polynomial. </p> <p> The term with the highest exponent is<tex>\\ 7x^3\\ </tex>, so the exponent of 3 would be the degree of this polynomial. </p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:37:58'),(26,2,'Multiplying Polynomials using the Distributive Property ','What is the result after using the distributive property? ','\\left(4x- 5 \\right)\\left(2x^2+ 16x +20 \\right) ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','8x^3\\ +\\ 74x^2\\ +\\ 160x\\ -100 ','8x^3\\ -\\ 36x^2\\ -\\ 100 ','8x^3\\ +70x^2\\ -\\ 100 ',' 8x^3\\ +54x^2\\ -\\ 100 ',NULL,'8x^3\\ +54x^2\\ -\\ 100',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> \\left(4x\\ -\\ 5\\right)\\left(2x^2\\ +\\ 16x\\ +\\ 20\\right) </tex></p> <p> To solve this using the distributive property, we need to multiply 4x and 5 to EACH term inside the 2nd set of parentheses. </p> <p> <tex> 4x\\cdot 2x^2 = 8x^3\\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\left(-5\\right)\\cdot 2x^2 = -10x^2 </tex> </p> <p> <tex> 4x \\cdot  16x = 64x^2\\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\left(-5\\right)\\cdot  16x = -80x </tex> </p> <p> <tex> 4x \\cdot 20 = 80x\\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\left(-5\\right)\\cdot 20 = -100 </tex> </p> <p> Now put the respective signs on each term, put them together and combine like terms to get the final answer. </p> <p> <tex> 8x^3 + 64x^2 - 10x^2 + 80x - 80x - 100 </tex> </p> <p> <tex> 8x^3 + 54x^2 -100 </tex> </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 15:00:16'),(27,2,'Dividing Polynomials by Monomials ','What is the resulting polynomial after division?','\\frac{12x^3\\ -\\ 8x^2\\ +\\ 16x\\ +\\ 20}{4x} ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','3x^2\\ +\\ 2x\\ +\\ 4\\ +\\ \\frac{5}{x} ','3x^2\\ -\\ 2x\\ +\\ 4\\ +\\ \\frac{5}{x}','8x^2\\ -\\ 4x\\ +\\ 12\\ +\\ \\frac{16}{x}','3x^3\\ -\\ 2x^2\\ +\\ 4x\\ +\\ \\frac{5}{x} ',NULL,'3x^2\\ -\\ 2x\\ +\\ 4\\ +\\ \\frac{5}{x} ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> \\frac{12x^3\\ -\\ 8x^2\\ +\\ 16x\\ +\\ 20}{4x} </tex></p> <p> First split up the numerator and divide EACH term by 4x.</p> <p><tex> \\frac{12x^3}{4x}\\ =\\ 3x^2\\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\frac{16x}{4x}=\\ 4 </tex></p> <p><tex> \\frac{-8x^2}{4x}\\ =\\ -2x\\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\frac{20}{4x}=\\ \\frac{5}{x} </tex></p> <p> Now combine the terms together with their respective signs to get the final answer. </p> <p><tex> 3x^2\\ -\\ 2x\\ +\\ 4\\ +\\ \\frac{5}{x} </tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:45:20'),(28,2,'Adding and Subtracting Polynomials ',' What polynomial is the result of subtracting these two polynomials? ','5x^2\\ +\\ 2x\\ +\\ 12\\ \\ -\\ \\ x^2\\ -\\ 10x\\ +\\ 2 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','4x^2\\ -\\ 8x\\ +10 ',' 4x^2\\ +\\ 12x\\ +\\ 14 ','4x^2\\ +\\ 12x\\ +\\ 10 ','-4x^2\\ +\\ 12x\\ +\\ 10',NULL,'4x^2\\ +\\ 12x\\ +\\ 10',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> 5x^2\\ +\\ 2x\\ +\\ 12\\ \\ -\\ \\ x^2\\ -\\ 10x\\ +\\ 2 </tex></p><p> Before subtracting the polynomials, make sure to change the SIGN of the terms in the 2nd polynomial.</p> <p><tex> -x^2\\ +\\ 10x\\ -\\ 2 </tex></p> <p> Follow the same steps that would be done for adding polynomials here.</p> <p><tex> 5x^2 + 2x + 12 </tex></p> <p><tex> \\frac{-x^2\\ +\\ 10x\\ -2}{4x^2\\ +12x\\ +\\ 10} </tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:41:51'),(29,2,'Multiplying Polynomials using FOIL','What trinomial results from the multiplication of these 2 binomials? ','\\left(2x\\ -\\ 4\\right)\\ \\left(x-3\\right) ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','2x^2\\ -\\ 7x\\ +\\ 12 ','2x^2\\ -\\ 10x\\ +\\ 12 ',' 2x^2\\ -\\ 10x\\ -\\ 12 ','2x^2\\ +\\ 10x\\ +\\ 12 ',NULL,'2x^2\\ -\\ 10x\\ +\\ 12 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p> <tex> \\left(2x\\ -\\ 4\\right)\\ \\left(x-3\\right) </tex> </p> <p> To multiply these binomials, use FOIL! FOIL stands for First Outer Inner Last. Do these steps to find the trinomial that results from multiplying these binomials. </p> <p><tex> First (F) \\ -2x\\ \\cdot \\ x\\ =\\ 2x^2 </tex></p> <p><tex> Outer (O) \\ -2x\\ \\cdot \\ \\left(-3\\right)=\\ -6x </tex></p> <p><tex> Inner (I) \\ -x\\ \\ \\cdot \\ \\left(-4\\right)\\ =\\ -4x </tex></p> <p><tex> Last (L) \\ -\\left(-4\\right)\\ \\cdot \\ \\left(-3\\right)\\ =\\ 12 </tex></p> <p> Put the terms together with their respective signs and combine like terms to get the final trinomial.</p> <p><tex> 2x^2\\ -\\ 6x\\ -\\ 4x\\ +\\ 12 </tex></p> <p><tex> 2x^2\\ -\\ 10x\\ +\\ 12 </tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:42:18'),(30,2,'Dividing Polynomials by Monomials ','What is the resulting polynomial after division? ','\\frac{4x^2y^2\\ +10xy\\ -\\ 40}{2xy} ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','2xy\\ +\\ 5\\ -\\ \\frac{20}{xy} ',' 2xy\\ +\\ 5\\ +\\ \\frac{20}{xy}','2xy\\ +\\ 8\\ -\\ \\frac{38}{xy}','2xy\\ +\\ 5\\ -\\ \\frac{20}{x}',NULL,'2xy\\ +\\ 5\\ -\\ \\frac{20}{xy} ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p> <tex> \\frac{4x^2y^2\\ +10xy\\ -\\ 40}{2xy} </tex> </p> <p> First split up the numerator and divide EACH term by 2xy. </p> <p> <tex> \\frac{4x^2y^2}{2xy}\\ =\\ 2xy\\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\frac{10xy}{2xy}\\ =\\ 5 </tex> </p> <p> <tex> \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\frac{-40}{2xy}\\ =\\ \\frac{-20}{xy} </tex> </p> <p> Now combine the terms together with their respective signs to get the final answer. </p> <p> <tex> \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ \\ 2xy\\ +\\ 5-\\ \\frac{20}{xy} </tex> </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 14:42:52'),(31,4,'Different Forms of Quadratics','Convert this quadratic from vertex form to standard form.','y = (x - 3)^2 - 2',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y = x^2 + 6x - 11','y = x^2 + 6x + 7','y = x^2 - 6x + 7','y = x^2 - 6x - 11',NULL,'y = x^2 - 6x + 7',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>y = (x - 3)<sup>2</sup> - 2</p> <p>To convert from vertex form to standard form, FOIL out (x - 3)<sup>2</sup> as (x - 3)(x - 3) and then subtract 2 from the result.</p> <p>y = (x - 3)(x - 3) - 2</p> <p>y = x<sup>2</sup> - 6x + 9 - 2</p> <p>y = x<sup>2</sup> - 6x + 7</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:28'),(32,4,'Factoring Trinomials with Leading Coefficient Greater than 1','What is the factored form of this trinomial?','2x^2 + 6x - 20',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','(2x-5)\\ (x+4)','(2x + 10) (x - 2)','(2x - 4)\\ (x + 5)','(2x + 4)\\ (x - 5)',NULL,'(2x - 4) \\(x + 5)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>2x<sup>2</sup> + 6x - 20</p> <p>The first step is to determine what multiplies together to get 2x<sup>2</sup>. That is 2x and x, so remember to put each term in separate parentheses.</p> <p>Let\'s write down the factor pairs of 20:</p><p> Factor Pairs of 20: 1 and 20, 2 and 10, 4 and 5</p> <p>We can get rid of 1 and 20 because multiplying x or 2x by 20 and multiplying the other term by 1 is not going to get us 6x. Same thing with 2 and 10. So we are left with 4 and 5.</p> <p>The larger number is positive and is being multiplied by 2x (so in its parentheses would be 2x - 4) and the smaller number is negative and is multiplied by x (so the parentheses would be x + 5). Write this for the answer.</p> <p>(2x - 4)(x + 5)</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 14:12:29'),(33,4,'Special Cases for Factoring Trinomials','What is the factored form of this polynomial?','2x^2 - 98',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','(x - 7)\\ (x + 7) ','2(x - 7)\\ (x + 7)','(2x - 7)\\ (x + 7)','(2x - 49)\\ (x + 49)',NULL,'2(x - 7)\\ (x + 7)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>2x^2 - 98</tex></p><p>The first step is to factor out the GCF since there is one here that is greater than 1. Factor out a 2 from this polynomial.</p> <p><tex>2\\left (x^2 -49  \\right )</p> </tex><p>Hopefully, you recognized that this is a special case of difference of squares! Take the square root of <tex>x^2</tex> (x) and 49 (7) and put them in separate parentheses, one with a - sign between them and the other with a + sign between them.</p> <p><tex>2(x - 7)\\ (x + 7)</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 14:14:50'),(34,4,'Factoring Trinomials','What is the factored form of this trinomial?','x^2 - 7x + 12',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','(x - 10)\\ (x + 3)','(x - 3)\\ (x - 4)','(x + 3)\\ (x + 4)','(x - 5)\\ (x - 2)',NULL,'(x - 3)\\ (x - 4)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>x^2 - 7x + 12</tex></p><p>The first step is to determine what multiplies together to get <tex>x^2</tex>. That is x and x, so remember to put each term in separate parentheses.</p> <p>Since the sign of the last term of the trinomial is positive and the sign of the middle term of the trinomial is negative, both factors have a negative sign.</p> <p>Now let\'s write out the factor pairs of 12 and try to find one that sums up to 7.</p> <p>Factor Pairs of 12: 1 and 12, 2 and 6, 3 and 4</p> <p>Since the factor pair that sums up to 7 is 3 and 4, put those in parentheses along with the x term and - sign already in each parentheses.</p> <p><tex>(x - 3)(x - 4)</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:09:24'),(35,4,'Quadratic Formula','What are the solutions to this quadratic?','x^2 - 9x + 12',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','x=\\frac{9\\pm \\sqrt{33}}{2}','x=\\frac{-9\\pm \\sqrt{33}}{2}','x=\\frac{9\\pm \\sqrt{129}}{2}','x=\\frac{-9\\pm \\sqrt{129}}{2}',NULL,'x=\\frac{9\\pm \\sqrt{33}}{2}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>x^2 - 9x + 12</tex></p> <p>This quadratic cannot be factored the regular way, so we need to use the quadratic formula. Remember that the a value is in front of <tex>x^2</tex> (1), the b value is in front of x (-9) and the c value is the constant (12).</p> <p><tex>x=\\frac{-b\\pm \\sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a} </tex></p> <p><tex>x=\\frac{-(-9)\\pm \\sqrt{(-9)^{2}-4(1)(12)}}{2(1)}</tex> </p><p><tex>x=\\frac{9\\pm \\sqrt{81-48}}{2}</tex></p><p> <tex>x=\\frac{9\\pm \\sqrt{33}}{2}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:29'),(36,4,'Factoring Trinomials with Leading Coefficient Greater than 1','What is the factored form of this trinomial?','4x^2 + 4x - 15',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','(4x - 5)\\ (x + 3) ','(2x + 5)\\ (2x + 3)','(2x - 5)\\ (2x - 3)','(2x - 3)\\ (2x + 5)',NULL,'(2x - 3)\\ (2x + 5)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>4x^2 + 4x - 15</tex></p> <p>The first step is to determine what multiplies together to get <tex>4x^2</tex>. That is 2x and 2x (x and 4x would not work here because when multiplying it by the factors of 15. you would not get 4). Remember to put these in separate parentheses.</p> <p>Let\'s write down the factor pairs of 15:</p><p> Factor Pairs of 15: 1 and 15, 3 and 5</p> <p>We can get rid of 1 and 15 because multiplying 2x by 1 and 15 with any combination of + and - signs is not going to get us 4. So we are left with 3 and 5.</p><p>The larger number is positive and is being multiplied by 2x (so in its parentheses would be 2x - 3) and the smaller number is negative and is multiplied by 2x (so the parentheses would be 2x + 5). Write this for the answer.</p><p>(2x - 3)(2x + 5)</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 14:18:03'),(37,4,'Completing the Square','What are the solutions to this quadratic? Use completing the square -Don\'t factor it!','x^2 - 10x + 21',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','x = -7\\ and\\ x = -3 ','x = -3\\ and\\ x = 7','x = 3\\ and\\ x = 7','x = -7\\ and\\ x = 3',NULL,'x = 3\\ and\\ x = 7',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>x^2 - 10x + 21</tex></p> <p>The first step is to subtract 21 from both sides, making sure to leave a space between -10x and the equal sign on the left side.</p> <p><tex>x^2 - 10x +</tex> ____ = -21 </p> <p>Then divide -10 in half to get -5 and square -5 to get 25. Add 25 to both sides, filling it in for the dash on the left side.</p><p><tex>x^2-10x + 25 = -21 +25 </tex></p><p>Simplify the left to <tex> (x - 5)^2</tex> due to the negative perfect square trinomial and the right to 4.</p><p><tex>(x - 5)^2 = 4 </tex></p> <p>Take the square root of both sides and find the 2 solutions of x.</p><p><tex>x-5=2 \\rightarrow x=7</tex> </p><p><tex> x-5=-2 \\rightarrow x=3 </tex> </p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:17:12'),(38,4,'Different Forms of Quadratics','Convert this quadratic from standard form to vertex form.','x^2 - 12x + 29',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y=(x + 6)^2 + 137','y=(x + 6)^2 - 7','y = (x - 6)^2 - 7','y = (x - 6)^2 + 137',NULL,'y = (x - 6)^2 - 7',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>x^2 - 12x + 29</tex></p><p>To convert from standard form to vertex form, first find the x-coordinate of the vertex by doing x = -b/2a.</p> <p><tex>x=\\frac{-\\left(-12\\right)}{2\\left(1\\right)} =\\frac{12}{2} = 6</tex></p><p>Plug in 6 for x in the original quadratic to get the y-coordinate of the vertex.</p> <p><tex>y = 6^2- 12(6) + 29</tex></p><p><tex>y = 36 - 72 + 29</tex></p><p><tex>y= 7</tex></p><p>Plug this vertex (6, 7) into vertex form.</p><p> <tex> y = (x - 6)^2- 7 </tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 14:26:01'),(39,4,'Factor by Grouping','What is the factored form of this polynomial?','2x^3 + 8x^2 - 3x - 12',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','(2x^2 - 4) \\ (x - 3)','(2x + 4) \\ (x - 3)','(2x^2 - 3)\\ (x + 4)','(2x^2 + 4)\\ (x - 3)',NULL,'(2x^2 - 3)\\ (x + 4)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>2x^3 + 8x^2 - 3x - 12</tex></p> <p>In order to factor by grouping, split this polynomial into 2 terms each <tex>(2x^3\\  and\\ 8x^2)\\ and\\ (-3x - 12) </tex>before factoring the GCF out of each part.</p><p><tex>y = 2x^2(x + 4) - 3(x + 4)</p><p>Remember that the factor inside the parentheses should be the same or you need to factor out a different GCF!</p><p>Put <tex> 2x^2 </tex> and 3 into a set of parentheses along with x + 4 to get the fully factored form.</p> <p><tex>y = (2x^2 - 3) (x + 4)</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:14:07'),(40,4,'Special Cases for Factoring Trinomials','What is the factored form of this polynomial?','x^2 + 18x + 81',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','(x + 9)\\ (x + 9)','(x - 9)\\ (x - 9)','(x - 9)\\ (x + 9)','(x + 40) \\ (x + 41)',NULL,'(x + 9) \\(x + 9)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>x^2+ 18x + 81</p> <p>Hopefully, you recognized that this is a special case of the positive perfect square trinomial! Divide 18 by 2 (which is 9) and put that term and x in 2 parentheses, both with a + sign between them.</p> <p>(x + 9) (x + 9)</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:14:07'),(41,10,'Absolute Value Inequalities','What are the solutions to this inequality?','\\left|2x+3\\right|<\\ 67',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','x\\ <\\ 32\\ and\\ x\\ >\\ -35','x\\ >\\ 32\\ and\\ x\\ <\\ -35 ','x\\ >\\ -32\\ and\\ x\\ <\\ 35 ','x\\ <\\ -32\\ and\\ x\\ >\\ 35 ',NULL,'<\\ 32\\ and\\ x\\ >\\ -35  ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,' <p>|2x+3|&lt;67 </p><p> To solve this absolute value inequality, we need to make 2 inequalities, the first with 67 and the second with -67. Remember that the inequality with -67\'s sign has to be flipped after we solve for x. </p><p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/avf1.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:40:49'),(42,10,'Absolute Value Equations ','What are the values of x in this equation? Only type in the number for both. The first answer box is for the negative solution and the second answer box is for the positive solution.','\\left|x\\ +\\ 10\\right|\\ =\\ 23 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'x = ','x = ','','13','-33',NULL,'<p><tex> \\left|x\\ +\\ 10\\right|\\ =\\ 23 </tex></p><p> To solve this absolute value equation, we need to make 2 equations, one that is equal to 23 and the other that is equal to -23. Then, solve each equation to get the 2 solutions for this equation. </p> <p><img src=\"http://4.24