,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 18:11:16'),(46,10,'Absolute Value Transformations ','What is the range of this absolute value function? ','y\\ =\\ \\left|x+5\\right| ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\left[-5,\\ \\infty \\right) ',' \\left[5,\\ \\infty \\right)','\\left[-5,\\ 0\\right]','\\left[0,\\ \\infty \\right)',NULL,'\\left[0,\\ \\infty \\right) ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> y\\ =\\ \\left|x+5\\right| </tex></p> <p> Remember that the range of an absolute value of function that is translated HORIZONTALLY is always [0, ∞). </p> <p> So the range for this function would be: </p> <p> [0, ∞) </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 18:11:39'),(47,10,'Absolute Value Equations ','What are the values of x in this equation? Only type in the number for both. The first answer box is for the negative solution and the second answer box is for the positive solution.','\\left|7x\\right|\\ =\\ 49 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'x = ','x = ',NULL,'7','-7',NULL,'<p><tex> \\left|7x\\right|\\ =\\ 49 </tex></p> <p> To solve this absolute value equation, we need to make 2 equations, one that is equal to 49 and the other that is equal to -49. Then, solve each equation to get the 2 solutions for this equation. </p><p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/avf6.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 18:44:10'),(48,10,'Absolute Value Inequalities ','What are the solutions to this inequality? ','\\left|3x\\right|\\ <\\ 42 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','x\\ <\\ 14\\  and\\ x\\ <\\ -14 ','x\\ <\\ 14\\ \\ and\\ \\ x\\ >\\ -14 ','x\\ >\\ 14\\ \\ and\\ \\ x\\ <\\ -14 ','x\\ >\\ 14\\ \\ and\\ \\ x\\ >\\ -14 ',NULL,'x\\ <\\ 14\\  and\\ x\\ <\\ -14 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p> |3x| < 42 </p><p> To solve this absolute value inequality, we need to make 2 inequalities, the first with 42 and the second with -42. Remember that the inequality with -42\'s sign has to be flipped after we solve for x. </p><p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/avf2.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 18:27:27'),(49,10,'Absolute Value Transformations','Absolute value functions can only be reflected over what axis (type either x or y into the answer, exactly as you see it here)? ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'y',NULL,NULL,'<p> Remember that absolute value functions can ONLY be reflected over the y-axis because absolute value is ALWAYS positive, so trying to reflect an absolute value function over the x-axis (where the parent graph is |-x|) will end up keeping the graph positive. </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:29'),(50,10,'Absolute Value Equations ','What are the values of x in this equation? Only type in the number for both. The first answer box is for the negative solution and the second answer box is for the positive solution. ','\\left|2x\\ -\\ 4\\right|\\ =\\ 36',NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'x = ','x = ',NULL,'20','-16',NULL,'<p> <tex>\\left|2x\\ -\\ 4\\right|\\ =\\ 36 </tex></p> <p> To solve this absolute value equation, we need to make 2 equations, one that is equal to 32 and the other that is equal to -32. Then, solve each equation to get the 2 solutions for this equation. </p><p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/avf3.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 18:27:27'),(51,5,'Multi-Step Inequalities ','What is the solution to this inequality?  ','4x + 10 \\leq 2x - 6  ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','x \\leq -8  ','x \\geq -8 ','x \\geq 8 ','x \\leq 8 ',NULL,'x \\leq -8 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>4x + 10 \\leq 2x - 6</tex></p> <p>To solve this inequality, we need to move the CONSTANTS to one side of the inequality and VARIABLES to the other side of the inequality before doing division to solve for x.</p> <p>When we move variables to the left and constants to the right (subtracting 2x from both sides and subtracting 10 from both sides), we can solve for x.</p><p> <tex>4x + 10 \\leq 2x - 6</tex></p><p><tex>2x \\leq -16</tex></p><p><tex>x \\leq -8</tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:51:04'),(52,5,'Literal Equations  ','Given this literal equation, solve for y.  ','h = 3gy + br  ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\frac{h+br}{3g} ','\\frac{h-3g}{br} ','\\frac{h-br}{3g} ','\\frac{h+3g}{br} ',NULL,'\\frac{h-br}{3g}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>h = 3gy + br</p> <p><p>To solve for y in this literal equation, we need to subtract br from both sides to ISOLATE the term with y. Then, divide by what is attached to y (3g) to get y by itself.</p> <p><tex>h = 3gy + br</tex></p> <p><tex>h- br = 3gy</tex></p> <p><tex>\\frac{h-br}{3g} = y </tex> </p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:22:22'),(53,5,'One-Step and Two-Step Equations  ','What is the value of x in this equation? (Only type in the number) ','5x - 2 = 53  ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'x=',NULL,NULL,'11',NULL,NULL,'<p>5x - 2 = 53</p> <p>To solve this two-step equation, we want to add 2 to both sides to get a one-step equation. Then, divide both sides by 5 to get x by itself.</p> <p>5x - 2 = 53</p> <p><u>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+2 &nbsp;&nbsp;+2&nbsp;</u></p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<tex>\\frac{5x}{5} =</tex> &nbsp;&nbsp;<tex>\\frac{55}{5}</tex></p> <p><tex>x = 11</tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:54:12'),(54,5,'Two-Variable Inequality and Equation Word Problems  ','Michaels\'s supermarket sells 2 different kinds of fruits: apples and oranges. Last Tuesday, Michael sold 150 fruits and earned $1,200 in revenue with oranges being $3 and apples being $2. Write 2 equations to represent the fruits bought at Michael\'s supermarket last Tuesday if x is the number of apples and y is the number of oranges bought.  ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','x + y = 150\\ and\\ 3x + 2y = 1,200 ','x + y = 150\\ and\\ 2x + 3y = 1,200  ','x + y = 1,200\\ and\\ 2x + 3y = 150',NULL,NULL,'x + y = 150\\ and\\ 2x + 3y = 1,200 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>When dealing with word problems in algebra, it is essential that you determine the most important information you need to write the equations. For this problem: the most important sentence is:</p> <p>Last Tuesday, Michael sold 150 fruits and earned $1,200 in revenue with oranges being $3 and apples being $2.</p> <p>Break this sentence down into parts to write your equations.</p> <p>Last Tuesday, Michael sold 150 fruits:</p> <p>x + y = 150</p> <p>He earned $1,200 in revenue with oranges being $3 and apples being $2:</p> <p>2x + 3y = 1,200</p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:57:58'),(55,5,'Compound Inequalities  ','What is the solution to this inequality?','x + 7 \\leq 16\\ or\\ 5x > 15 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','3 \\leq x \\leq 9 ','3 \\leq x < 9 ','3 < x < 9 ','3 < x \\leq 9 ',NULL,'3 < x \\leq 9',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>x + 7 <tex>\\leq</tex> 16 or 5x &gt; 15</p> <p>To solve this compound inequality, solve each inequality SEPARATELY before combining the 2 solutions together to get the final range of solution values of the compound inequality.</p> <tex>x + 7 \\leq 16</tex><p></p> <p><u>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -7 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;-7</u></p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <tex>x \\leq 9</tex></p><p></p> <tex>or</tex><p>&nbsp;</p> <tex>\\frac{5x}{5}</tex> &gt; <tex> \\frac{5}{5}</tex><p></p> <p>&nbsp; x &gt; 9</p> <p>The solution set of this compound inequality is between 3 and 9 (remember that the sign next to 3 has no line underneath it while the sign next to 9 has a line under it).</p> <p>3 < x <tex>\\leq </tex>9 </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:59:11'),(56,5,'One-Step and Two-Step Inequalities  ',' What is the solution to this inequality? ','-8x < 56 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','x < 7 ','x < -7','x > -7','x > 7',NULL,'x > -7 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>-8x &lt; 56</p> <p>To solve this inequality, we would need to divide by -8 to get x by itself. Remember to FLIP the inequality sign because we are dividing by the SAME NEGATIVE number on both sides of the inequality.</p> <tex>\\frac{-8x}{-8}</tex> &lt;<tex> \\frac{56} {-8}</tex> <p>x&gt;-7</p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:59:56'),(57,5,'Systems of Equations ','What is the solution (x and y) to this system of equations? Only type in the number for each.  ','2x + 5y = 10 \\\\ 4x + 3y = 34 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'x=  ','y=  ',NULL,'10','-2',NULL,'<p>2x + 5y = 10</p> <p>4x + 3y = 34</p> <p>We need to find a way to cancel a variable in the easiest way possible. Since 4 is a multiple of 2, multiply the TOP equation by -2 to cancel out the x\'s and then solve for y.</p> <p>&nbsp; -4x - 10y = -20</p> <p><u>+ 4x + 3y = 34&nbsp;</u></p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<tex>\\frac{-7y}{-7} = \\frac{14}{-7}</tex></p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; y = -2</p> <p>Plug in y = -2 into the top equation to find what x is.</p> <p>2x + 5(-2) = 10 &nbsp;</p> <p>2x - 10 = 10</p> <p>2x = 20</p> <p>x = 10</p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:29'),(58,5,'Multi-Step Equations  ','What is the value of x in this equation? (Only type in the number) ','5(x + 2) = 25 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'x=  ',NULL,NULL,'3',NULL,NULL,'<p>5(x + 2) = 25</p> <p>To solve this multi-step equation, let\'s think outside the box! We should divide 5 first to make this a one-step equation before subtracting 2 from both sides to get x by itself.</p> <tex>\\frac{5(x + 2)}{5} = \\frac{25} {5}</tex> <p>&nbsp;x + 2 = 5</p><p></p> <p><u>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -2 &nbsp;&nbsp;-2</u></p> <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; x = 3</p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:29'),(59,5,'Direct Variation Equations  ','If x = 8 when y = 16, what does x equal when y = 110? ','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'x=  ',NULL,NULL,'55',NULL,NULL,'<p>x = 8 when y = 16, x = ? when y = 110</p> <p>First find the constant of variation (k) between x = 8 and y = 16 to get the direct variation equation for this problem.</p> <p>y = kx</p> <p>16 = 8k</p> <p>k = 2</p> <p>y = 2x</p> <p>Plug in 110 for y into this equation to find x.</p> <p>110 = 2x</p> <p>x = 55</p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 14:03:27'),(60,5,'Graphing Inequalities ','What is the system of inequalities that represent this graph?',NULL,'Graphing-Inequalities-2.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y \\leq x+1 \\ and\\ y>2x ','y \\geq x+1 \\ and\\ y>2x ','y \\leq x+1 \\ and\\ y<2x ','y \\geq x+1 \\ and\\ y<2x',NULL,'y \\leq x+1 \\ and\\ y<2x ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Graphing-Inequalities-2.png\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>The red line has clean intersection points at (0, 1) and (1, 2). The blue has (0, 0) and (1, 2). Use these points to find the slope and y-intercept of each line (put it in slope-intercept form).</p> <p>Red: y = x + 1</p> <p>Blue: y = 2x</p> <p>Since the red line is solid, its inequality signs are <tex>\\leq or \\geq</tex> and since the blue line is dashed, its inequality signs are &lt; or &gt;.</p> <p>Since (0, 0) is shaded for the red line, its sign is <tex>\\leq</tex> and since (1, 0) is shaded for the blue line, its sign is &lt;.</p> <tex>y \\leq x + 1 and\\ y\\ \\ </tex> &lt;<tex>\\ \\ 2x</tex> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:31:46'),(61,7,'Exponential Growth and Decay','A new car has a value of $44,000. It depreciates 15% of its value every year. How much is the car worth in 4 years? Round to the nearest dollar (add commas between numbers if needed).Type only the number. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'y =',NULL,NULL,'22,968',NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> y\\ =\\ b\\left(a^x\\right) </tex> </p> <p> For this problem, we need to identify what b and a are. Remember b is our y-intercept/starting value ($44,000), a is our growth/decay factor (since this problem is decay, a is 1 - 0.15 = 0.85) and x is the number of years (4). Plug these numbers into the formula to get the answer.</p> <p> y = 44,000(0.85<sup>4</sup>)</p> <p> y = 44,000(0.52200625) </p> <p> y = $22,968</p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 15:50:31'),(62,7,'Continuously Compounded Interest ','Maya puts $150 into an account that earns 8% interest, compounded continuously. How much will be in the account in 3 years? Use the formula  A = Pe<sup>rt</sup> Type only the number. Round to the nearest dollar (add commas between numbers when necessary).','',NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'A=',NULL,NULL,'408',NULL,NULL,'<p> <tex>A\\ =\\ Pe^{rt} </tex> </p> <p> For this problem, we need to identify what we know from the question and what we need to find. </p> <p> We know that: </p> <p> P = $150 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;      r= 0.1&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;       t= 10 </p> <p>  rt = 0.1 * 10 = 1 </p> <p> Now plug these numbers for their respective variables to solve for A. </p> <p> <tex> A\\ =\\ \\left(150\\right)e^1 </p> <p><tex> A\\ =\\ 150e </tex> </p> <p> A = $408 </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:20:55'),(63,7,'Simple Interest ','Emily has $80 in a savings account that earns 6% per year. How much will she have in interest in 4 years if the interest is not compounded? Use the formula i = prt. Type only the number. Round to the nearest dollar (add commas between numbers if needed). ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'i=',NULL,NULL,'19',NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> i\\ =\\ prt </tex> </p> <p> For this problem, we need to identify what we know from the question and what we need to find. </p> <p> We know that: </p> <p>  p = $ 80&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; r = 0.06&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  t=4 </p> <p> Now plug these numbers for their respective variables to solve for i. </p> <p> i = (80)(0.06)(4) </p> <p>  i = $19</p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 16:16:49'),(64,7,'Exponential Growth and Decay ','Does the following graph show exponential growth or decay? {Type either Growth or Decay in the text box, exactly as you see it here). ',NULL,'Exponential-Growth.png',NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Growth',NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Exponential-Growth.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> To determine if this graph is exponential growth or decay, look to see where it is coming from and where it is going on the graph. Since it is going from the bottom left to the top right, it is exponential GROWTH (compared to top left to bottom right, which is exponential DECAY). </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:22:51'),(65,7,'Graphing Exponential Functions ','What is the equation represented by this graph? ',NULL,'Exponential-Function-2.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y\\ =\\ 0.25^x ','y\\ =\\ 2^x','y\\ =\\ 0.5^x','y\\ =\\ 0.5\\left(1^x\\right) ',NULL,'y\\ =\\ 0.5^x',NULL,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Exponential-Function-2.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> To find out the equation of this graph, first find the y-intercept of the graph. That would be (0, 1), so it will not be a part of the equation. Look for another point on the graph that can help us identify this equation. That would be (1, 0.5). Since the formula is <tex>y = b \\left(a^x\\right) </tex> and b is 1, a would be 0.5, since <tex> 0.5^1 = 0.5. </tex> </p> <p> So the equation would be: </p> <p> <tex> y\\ =\\ 0.5^x </tex> </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:25:05'),(66,7,'Compound Interest ','Jason has $60 in an account that earns 14% compounded annually. To the nearest cent, how much will he have in 3 years? Use the formula B = p(1+ r)<sup>t</sup>. Type only the number. Round to the nearest dollar (add commas between numbers if necessary). ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'B= ',NULL,NULL,'89',NULL,NULL,'<p> <tex>B\\ =\\ p\\left(1+r\\right)^t </tex> </p> <p> For this problem, we need to identify what we know from the question and what we need to find. </p> <p> We know that: </p> <p>  P = $60&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;r=0.14&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;t = 3  </p> <p> 1 + r = 1.14</p> <p> Now plug these numbers for their respective variables to solve for B. </p> <p> <tex> B\\ =\\ \\left(60\\right)\\left(1.14^3\\right) </tex> </p> <p> <tex> B\\ =\\ \\left(60\\right)\\left(1.1481544\\right) </tex> </p> <p>  B = $89 </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:28:21'),(67,7,'Exponential Growth and Decay','Does the following graph show exponential growth or decay? {Type either Growth or Decay in the text box, exactly as you see it here). ',NULL,'Exponential-Decay.png',NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Decay',NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Exponential-Decay.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> To determine if this graph is exponential growth or decay, look to see where it is coming from and where it is going on the graph. Since it is going from the top left to the bottom right, it is exponential DECAY (compared to bottom left to top right, which is exponential GROWTH). </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:29'),(68,7,'Simple Interest ','If Matt earns $25 in interest in a savings account that earns 4% per year for 2 years, what is the original amount of money he put in the account? Use the formula i = prt. Type only the number.Round to the PE dollar (add commas between numbers if needed). ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'p=',NULL,NULL,'313',NULL,NULL,'<p> <tex>i\\ =\\ prt </tex> </p> <p> For this problem, we need to identify what we know from the question and what we need to find. </p> <p> We know that: </p> <p> i = $25&nbsp;&nbsp; r= 0.04&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; t= 2 </p> <p> Now plug these numbers for their respective variables to solve for p.</p> <p> <tex> 25\\ =\\ p\\left(0.04\\right)\\left(2\\right) </tex> </p> <p> <tex> 25\\ =\\ 0.08p </tex> </p> <p>  p = $313  </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 16:22:04'),(69,7,'Exponential Growth and Decay ','A town triples its population every 19 years. The current population of the town is 3,200 people. What will the population be in 114 years? Round to the nearest number. Put commas between numbers if necessary. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'23,32,800',NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> y\\ =\\ b\\left(a^x\\right) </tex> </p> <p> For this problem, we need to identify what b and a are. Remember b is our y-intercept/starting value (3,200). For a, it is 3 since we are tripling every 19 years. For x, we need to divide the number of years we are looking at (114) by the number of years it takes to triple (19) to get x (114/19 = 6). Plug these numbers into the equation to get the population after 114 years. </p> <p> <tex> y\\ =\\ 3,200\\left(3^6\\right) </tex> </p> <p> <tex> y\\ =\\ 3,200\\left(729\\right) </tex> </p> <p> <tex> y\\ =\\ 2,332,800\\ people </tex> </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 13:28:59'),(70,7,'Graphing Exponential Functions ',' What is the equation represented by this graph?',NULL,'Exponential-Function.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y\\ =\\ 2\\left(1^x\\right)','y\\ =\\ 0.5^x','y\\ =\\ 0.5\\left(2^x\\right) ','y\\ =\\ 2^x ',NULL,'y\\ =\\ 2^x',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Exponential-Function.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> To find out the equation of this graph, first find the y-intercept of the graph. That would be (0, 1), so it will not be a part of the equation. Look for another point on the graph that can help us identify this equation. That would be (1, 2). Since the formula is <tex>y\\ =\\ b\\left(a^x\\right) </tex> and b is 1, a would be 2, since <tex> 2^1\\ =\\ 2. </tex> </p>  <p> So the equation would be: </p> <p> <tex> y\\ =\\ 2^x </tex> </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:29'),(71,9,'Two-Way Frequency Tables ','What is the probability that someone in the table likes a SUV?',NULL,'Two-way-Frequency-Tables.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\frac{135}{240} ','\\frac{21}{240}','\\frac{84}{240}','\\frac{156}{240}',NULL,'\\frac{156}{240}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Two-way-Frequency-Tables.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>  <p>The key to these problems is understanding the wording of the question. For this problem, someone in the table refers to all participants (240, our denominator) and those who like SUV\'s refers to the total in the SUV column (156, our numerator). Put the numerator over the denominator in a fraction to get the final answer.</p> <p><tex>\\frac{156}{240}</tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:43:13'),(72,9,'Interpreting Statistical Models','What is the mean of the data in this model? Use your calculator to get the answer. ',NULL,'Bar-Graph-Mean.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','2.5','3.5','4.48','2.09',NULL,'2.09',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Bar-Graph-Mean.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> To find the mean of the bar graph, multiply the frequency times the number of children and divide it by the total frequency for all of the children. </p> <p> <p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/ps1.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 07:14:48'),(73,9,'Interpreting Statistical Models','What is the interquartile range of the data in this model?',NULL,'Box-and-whisker-plot-IQR.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','24','43','36','29',NULL,'24',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Box-and-whisker-plot-IQR.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> The interquartile range refers to subtracting the 1st quartile from the 3rd quartile. On a box and whisker plot, this translates to subtracting the left edge of the box from the right edge. The right edge is at the value 90 and the left edge is at the value 66. </p> <p> So when we do 90-66, we get our answer of: </p> <p> 24</p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:29'),(74,9,'Different Types of Statistical Models ','What is this type of function called? ',NULL,'dot-plot.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','BarGraph','Histogram','Dot\\ Plot','Scatter\\ Plot',NULL,'Dot\\ Plot',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/dot-plot.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>  <p> This model is called a dot plot because of the dots that are at the values in the model. </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:35:59'),(75,9,'Lines of Best Fit','What is the line of best fit for this model?',NULL,'Lines-of-Best-Fit.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y\\ =\\ 2x','y\\ =\\ x','y\\ =\\ 2x\\ +\\ 20','y\\ =\\ x\\ +\\ 20',NULL,'y\\ =\\ x',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Lines-of-Best-Fit.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>  <p> To do lines of best fit, which are linear lines, find 2 points that the graph approaches APPEOXIMATELY. 2 points that you could use are (20, 20) and (40, 40). Find the slope and y-intercept of this line to find the line of best fit. *The points you use for slope and y-intercept don\'t have to be the same - only the line does!* </p> <p> Slope = <tex> \\frac{40-20}{40-20}\\ =\\ \\frac{20}{20}\\ =\\ 1 </tex></p> <p><tex> y\\ =\\ x\\ +\\ b\\ \\rightarrow \\ 40\\ =\\ 40\\ +\\ b\\ \\rightarrow \\ b\\ =\\ 0 </tex></p> <p><tex> y\\ =\\ x\\ </tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:37:12'),(76,9,'Interpreting Statistical Models ','What is the mode of the data in this model?',NULL,'Stem-and-Leaf-Plot-Mode.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','38','32','8','29',NULL,'38',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Stem-and-Leaf-Plot-Mode.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> The mode refers to the number that appears the MOST in a dataset. Since we read stem-and-leaf plots as the first number being the stem and the second number being the leaf, 38 is the mode of this plot. </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:29'),(77,9,'Interpreting Statistical Models','What is the range of the data in this model?',NULL,'Bar-Graph-Mean-1.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','6','28','29','5',NULL,'6',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Bar-Graph-Mean-1.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> To find the range of a bar graph, take the highest value on the x-axis and subtract the lowest value on the x-axis from it. </p> <p> *Do NOT subtract frequencies - This is wrong because frequencies is how much the value on the x-axis appears in the dataset* </p> <p> 6 - 0 = 6 </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:38:12'),(78,9,'Different Types of Statistical Models','What is this type of function called?',NULL,'Histogram.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','Histogram','Pie\\ Chart','Bar\\ Graph','Line\\ Graph',NULL,'Histogram',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Histogram.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> This model is called a histogram because it has bars that TOUCH, which separates it from being just a bar graph (Each bar also represents a RANGE of values, while a bar in a bar graph represents INDIVIDUAL values). </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:39:12'),(79,9,'Interpreting Statistical Models','What is the median of the data in this model?',NULL,'Dot-Plot-Median.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','4','6','3','5',NULL,'5',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Dot-Plot-Median.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> To find the median of a dot plot, start by crossing out the first dot on the left and then the first dot on the right. Keep crossing out the dots one by one on each side until you get to the dot in the middle, which should be at 5. </p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:30'),(80,9,'Two-Way Frequency Tables','What is the probability that a male likes a sports car?',NULL,'Two-way-Frequency-Tables-1.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\frac{39}{84}','\\frac{39}{60}','\\frac{39}{240}','\\frac{39}{180}',NULL,'\\frac{39}{84}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Two-way-Frequency-Tables-1.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p> The key to these problems is understanding the wording of the question. For this problem, those who like sports cars refers to the total number of individuals who like sports cars (84, the denominator) and males refers to males who like sports cars since the males in the question refer to those who like sports cars (39, the numerator). Put the numerator over the denominator as a fraction for the answer. </p> <p><tex> \\frac{39}{84} </tex></p> ',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:39:12'),(81,8,'Different Forms of Linear Functions','Write the equation of the line with an x-intercept of (6, 0) and a y-intercept of (0, 4) in standard form.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','6x\\ +\\ 4y\\ =\\ 24','4x\\ +\\ 6y\\ =\\ 24','4x\\ -\\ 6y\\ =\\ 24','6x\\ -\\ 4y\\ =\\ 24',NULL,'4x\\ +\\ 6y\\ =\\ 24',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p> <tex>x\\ :\\ \\left(6,0\\right)\\ and\\ \\ y\\ :\\ \\left(0,4\\right)</tex></p><p>Before we write this equation in standard form, it would be helpful to write this inslope-intercept form.Find the slope and use the intercept to write the equation in this form.</p> <p><tex>Slope= \\frac{4-0}{0-6}\\ =\\ \\frac{-4}{6}\\ =\\ \\frac{-2}{3}</tex></p> <p><tex>y\\ =\\ \\frac{-2}{3}x\\ +\\ 4</tex></p><p>Multiply the entire equation by 6 to get rid of the fraction and add 4x to match the answer choices.</p><p><tex>6y\\ =\\ -4x\\ +\\ 24\\ \\rightarrow\\ 4x\\ +\\ 6y\\ =\\ 24</tex>.</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:13:08'),(82,8,'Finding Slope','What is the slope between these 2 points?','  (5,8)\\ and\\ (9,6)',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\frac{1}{2}','-2','\\frac{-1}{2}','2',NULL,'\\frac{-1}{2}',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>(5,8) and (9, 6)</p> <p>To find the slope between these points, remember change in y over change in x. The difference between the y-coordinates goes in the numerator and the difference between the x-coordinates go in the denominator.</p> <p><tex>Slope= \\frac{6-8}{9-5}\\ =\\ \\frac{-2}{4}\\ =\\ \\frac{-1}{2}</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:15:19'),(83,8,'Different Forms of Linear Functions','Write the equation of the line that has goes through (-3,0) and (5,8) in slope-intercept form.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y\\ =\\ x\\ +\\ 3','y\\ =\\ -x\\ +\\ 3','y\\ =\\ x\\ -\\ 3','y\\ =\\ -x\\ +\\ 13',NULL,'y\\ =\\ x\\ +\\ 3',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex>\\left(-3,\\ 0\\right)\\ and\\ \\left(5,\\ 8\\right)</tex></p> <p>In order to write the line that goes through the points in slope-intercept form, we need to find the slope (change in y over the change in x) and the y-intercept of the line. Find the slope first before plugging in one of the points to find the y-intercept (b).</p> <p><tex>slope =\\frac{8-0}{5\\ -\\ \\left(-3\\right)}\\ =\\ \\frac{8}{8}\\ =\\ 1</tex></p> <p><tex>y\\ =\\ x\\ +\\ b</tex></p> <p><tex>8\\ =\\ 5\\ +\\ b</tex></p> <p><tex>b\\ =\\ 3</tex></p> <p><tex>y\\ =\\ x\\ +\\ 3</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:15:19'),(84,8,'Different Forms of Linear Functions','Write the equation of the line containing (-1,5) and a slope of 5 in point-slope form.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y\\ +\\ 5\\ =\\ 5\\left(x\\ +\\ 1\\right)','y\\ +\\ 5\\ =\\ 5\\left(x\\ -\\ 1\\right)','y\\ -\\ 5\\ =\\ 5\\left(x\\ -\\ 1\\right)','y\\ -\\ 5\\ =\\ 5\\left(x\\ +\\ 1\\right)',NULL,'y\\ -\\ 5\\ =\\ 5\\left(x\\ +\\ 1\\right)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>Slope :<tex>5\\ \\ and\\ \\ Point\\ :\\ \\left(-1,\\ 5\\right)</tex></p> <p>For point-slope form, all we need is a point and the slope of the line. Since both are provided in the question, we just have to make sure we are plugging them in correctly. Watch your signs!</p> <p><tex> y\\ -\\ y_1\\ =\\ m\\left(x\\ -\\ x_1\\right)</tex></p> <p><tex>y\\ -\\ 5\\ =\\ 5\\left(x\\ -\\ \\left(-1\\right)\\right)</tex></p> <p><tex>y\\ -\\ 5\\ =\\ 5\\left(x\\ +\\ 1\\right)</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:30'),(85,8,'Key Features of Linear Functions (Graphs)','What is the y-intercept of the following line?',NULL,'Y-intercept-Question.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\left(-2,\\ 0\\right)','\\left(0,\\ 2\\right)','\\left(0,\\ -2\\right)','\\left(-2,\\ 0\\right)',NULL,'\\left(0,\\ -2\\right)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Y-intercept-Question.png\" alt=\"\" /></p> <p>To find the y-intercept of the line, simply look to see where it crosses the y-axis. Since the line touches the y-axis at -2, the y-intercept is (0, -2) - Remember -2 is the y-coordinate so it is written as a coordinate point.</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-04 05:46:57'),(86,8,'Different Forms of Linear Functions','Convert the line below from point-slope form to slope-intercept form.','y\\ +\\ 3=\\ 4(x-4)',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y\\ =\\ 4x\\ +\\ 19','y\\ =\\ 4x\\ +\\ 13','y\\ =\\ 4x\\ -\\ 13','y\\ =\\ 4x\\ -\\ 19',NULL,'y\\ =\\ 4x\\ -\\ 19',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><tex> y\\ +\\ 3=\\ 4(x-4)</tex></p> <p>To convert from point-slope form to slope-intercept form (y=mx+b), we are going to distribute 4 on the right side of the equation to each term before subtracting 3 from both sides to get y by itself and the correct form.</p> <p><tex> y\\ +\\ 3\\ =\\ 4x\\ -\\ 16</tex></p> <p><tex>y\\ =\\ 4x\\ -\\ 19</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:27:08'),(87,8,'Finding Slope','Joe works as a barista at a coffee shop. If Joe makes $30 in 2 weeks and $60 in 4 weeks, how much money does Joe make every week?',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\$15 ','\\$30 ','\\$28 ','\\$2 ',NULL,'\\$15 ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>$30 in 2 weeks and $60 in 4 weeks.</p> <p>To find the slope in this real-life problem, you need to find the change in the money Joe is making (like the y in this situation) and divide it by the change in the number of weeks Joe is working (like the x in this situation).</p><p><tex>slope =\\frac{60\\ -\\ 30}{4\\ -\\ 2}\\ =\\ \\frac{30}{2}\\ =\\ \\$15</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:27:08'),(88,8,'Key Features of Linear Functions (Graphs)','What is the sign of the slope of this line (Type either Positive or Negative, exactly as you see it here for your answer)?',NULL,'Sign-Slope-Question.png',NULL,NULL,'TEXT',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Negative',NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Sign-Slope-Question.png\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>To find the sign of the slope of a line, we need to look at whether the line goes from the bottom left to top right of the graph (making it positive) or the top left to the bottom right of the graph (making it negative). Since this line here is showing the latter, the sign of this line\'s slope is negative.</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-03-30 17:59:30'),(89,8,'Different Forms of Linear Functions','Convert the line below from standard form to slope-intercept form.','4x\\ +\\ 2y=\\ 12',NULL,NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','y\\ =\\ -2x\\ +\\ 6','y\\ =\\ 2x\\ +\\ 6','y\\ =\\ -2x\\ +\\ 12','y\\ =\\ 2x\\ +\\ 12',NULL,'y\\ =\\ -2x\\ +\\ 6',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p>4x + 2y = 12</p><p>To convert this line from standard form to slope-intercept form, we need to solve for y. We can do this by subtracting 4x from both sides of the equation and dividing by 2 to get y by itself. </p> <p> 4x + 2y = 12</p> <p>2y = -4x + 12</p><p> y = -2x + 6</p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-04 05:53:12'),(90,8,'Key Features of Linear Functions (Graphs)','What is the slope of the following line?',NULL,'Slope-Question.png',NULL,NULL,'OBJECTIVE','\\frac{-1}{2}','-2','\\frac{1}{2}','2',NULL,'2',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'<p><img src=\"http://4.247.20.144:3000/Slope-Question.png\" alt=\"\" /></p><p>To find the slope of the line, find 2 clean points that you can find the slope of: (0, 0) and (1, 2). Plug these points into the slope formula, doing the change in y over the change in x.</p> <p><tex>slope=\\frac{2-0}{1-0}\\ =\\ \\frac{2}{1}\\ =\\ 2</tex></p>',1,NULL,NULL,500,NULL,'2023-04-03 07:42:06');
